solution: ```class RecentCounter {
    std::queue<int> q;
public:
    RecentCounter() {}

    int ping(int t) {
        q.push(t);
        while (q.front() < t - 3000) q.pop();
        return q.size();
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(1) amortized per ping
space complexity: O(1) amortized per ping
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Uses a FIFO queue to store timestamps. Each ping appends the new time and evicts all times older than t-3000. Because pings are strictly increasing, each element is enqueued and dequeued at most once, giving amortized O(1) cost and minimal memory footprint.

